<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How long does it take to meet someone?", answer: "There's no one answer — Pew Research surveys suggest the average single adult takes 6 to 18 months of active effort to enter a serious relationship. People in larger cities meet potential partners faster (more options) but take longer to commit (paradox of choice). Active daters who go on 2 to 4 dates per month find someone meaningful in roughly 6 to 12 months. Highly selective daters can take 2 to 5 years." },
  { question: "Is the calculator accurate?", answer: "It's a fun heuristic, not a prediction. The math uses three inputs — effort (how many dates per month), city size (dating pool), and selectivity (your hit rate). It multiplies them to estimate a timeline, which is consistent with general dating advice but not personalized. Real outcomes depend on luck, timing, where you look, and what you're looking for. Treat the result as a rough order of magnitude, not a calendar entry." },
  { question: "What if I haven't met anyone in years?", answer: "If you've been actively dating for 2+ years without success, look at three things: your dating pool (are you fishing in the right pond?), your selectivity (are you ruling people out too fast or too slow?), and your dating habits (are you actually going on dates, or just swiping?). Many long-term singles benefit from a 'meet 5 people in 2 weeks' challenge, which forces volume and breaks pattern paralysis." },
  { question: "Does effort really matter that much?", answer: "Yes — it's the single biggest variable. Going from 1 date a month to 4 dates a month doesn't just 4x your chances, it compounds them, because each date generates referrals, learning, and confidence. Studies of online dating show that the top 10% of users (by message volume and date frequency) match into relationships 5x faster than the bottom 50%. Effort beats almost everything." },
  { question: "Should I lower my standards to meet someone?", answer: "Not your standards — your filters. Standards are the things that genuinely matter: kindness, honesty, shared values. Filters are arbitrary preferences (height, profession, exact age). Lowering filters opens you up to great matches you'd otherwise rule out; lowering standards leads to relationships you regret. Most dating coaches recommend keeping the top 3 standards and dropping every other filter for the first few dates." }
]) %>

